            "id": "https://www.squareyards.com/blog/?p=31440",
            "url": "https://www.squareyards.com/blog/lets-dig-deep-into-the-grandeur-of-vadodaras-lakshmi-vilas-palace-2",
            "title": "Let\u2019s Dig Deep Into The Grandeur of Vadodara\u2019s Lakshmi Vilas Palace",
            "content_html": "\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">The Lakshmi Vilas Palace is one of the most magnificent mansions ever created, set among enormous gardens, mango orchards, and sweeping fields. It was commissioned in 1880 by Maharaja Sayajirao Gaekwad III and is four times the size of Buckingham Palace, with a total area of 700 acres.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">The magnificent palace, which was completed in about 1890 has been the residence of the Gaekwads, the rulers of the Princely State of Baroda, Gujarat for more than a century. The Palace compound includes numerous additional institutes, including the Baroda Golf Club, the Maharaja Fatehsinhrao Museum, and Motibaug Cricket Grounds, all of which are located inside its enormous property. The palace grounds are so large that they previously hosted a small zoo and a miniature train line to transport the royal children around. Due to the employment of domes, minarets, and arches, the palace is a perfect blend of Hindu, Mughal, and Gothic architectural styles.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-the-project-s-doomed-architect\"><strong>The Project&#8217;s Doomed Architect</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">The project&#8217;s lead architect Major Charles Mant was a well-known architect during his time. The Lakshmi Vilas was his most ambitious undertaking, having constructed palaces at Darbhanga, Bihar, and Kolhapur. Despite being an enthusiastic architect, he was believed to suffer from melancholy and paranoia, eventually leading to his death midway through the project.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">His death is said to have been the result of a suicide attempt motivated by fear. There are two theories as to what caused the anxiety or shame that drove him to such extremes. The first claims that he was concerned that his calculations were incorrect, and that the palace might collapse at any moment.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">The other claims that an inverted North symbol on the blueprints caused the palace to be erected in the mirror image of the design. As a result, the palace&#8217;s main entrance is on the backside. In any case, the architect died in the middle of the project, and Robert Fellows Chisolm was hired to take his place. Robert Fellows Chisholm, the designer architect, spent twelve years completing this magnificent edifice.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-the-magnificent-palace\"><strong>The Magnificent Palace</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">The palace was constructed for GBP 180,000 and had modern amenities such as elevators, an internal telephone system, and an electricity supply. The mansion was meant to be the most lavish edifice in the Baroda State, using materials sourced from all around the state. Even the building workers were only the best, and in some instances, they were even brought in from overseas.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">The palace&#8217;s facade is made of golden stone from Songadh mines, which gives it a distinctive golden light when seen in the dark and morning. The palace&#8217;s exterior is adorned with elements such as tiny domed &#8220;chattris&#8221; with finials, cusped arched entries, and jharokha windows, all in the Indo-Saracenic design. The outside is also decorated with finely carved stone patterns, brackets, and bands of carvings and paintings. In addition to these components, it also has a large structure that was supposed to be a clock tower but never turned out to be. Alternatively, a tiny red light was put on it to alert the populace if the monarch was there.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">Although the exteriors were the focus, the interiors are no less. The interiors are organized around two courtyards with trees and water fountains that quickly transport you to India&#8217;s tropical environment. The pleasant afternoons are provided by the trees and the water fountain, while the regal aspect is contributed by marble statues and cast-iron lamp posts. Aside from that, the interiors have been lavishly adorned with elaborate stucco work, paintings, foreign-made crystal chandeliers, stained glass windows, Venetian floor mosaics, exquisite furniture, and sculptures by Felici, the renowned Italian artist.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">This palace has enormous stairs with ornate marble railings and wide long hallways, much like any other palace. The palace is surrounded by these passageways, which give sufficient natural lighting and ventilation. The 170 large and tiny rooms are connected by magnificent stairways and long darkened hallways, some with themes such as the silver room or the gulabi (pink) room. The Darbar Hall is arguably the most remarkable of them, and without even viewing it, one cannot fully appreciate the palace&#8217;s magnificence.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\"><strong>The Darbar Hall:</strong> This great hall, which is approximately 5000 Sq. Ft in size is where the most exquisite music and dance events, as well as the most extravagant feasts, were held. The juxtaposing golden decorations above the arches and the dark brown wooden balconies gazing down from the first floor provide vitality to the hall, which is painted in a pale ivory tone.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">The intricate Venetian floor mosaic on the double-height hall&#8217;s floor contrasts with geometric designs in green and red on the ceiling. The bright belgian stained glass windows add to the overall effect. When the hall is lighted up with large crystal chandeliers echoing the hues of the ceilings and painting the space in a regal air, the entire design comes together.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\"><strong>The Gaddi Hall:</strong> The Gaddi Hall is famous for housing the throne, which has been occupied by numerous monarchs in the past. An amazing number of beautiful artworks are stitched throughout the extremely huge space. The paintings of Goddess Saraswati, Laxmi, and Lord Krishna, among others, are meticulously placed to create a feeling of harmony and balance.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\"><strong>The Pratap Shastragar:</strong> The Pratap Shastragar, or royal armoury, is located in a visitor-friendly section of the palace. The age-old weaponry that was previously used by the royal family and troops of the Baroda State Army are stored here, behind the enormous glass cases. The Rajratna Prof. Manikrao, the man who renovated the Jummadada Vyayam Mandir, selected this assortment.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\"><strong>The Gardens:</strong> William Goldring, a landscape architect from Kew Gardens, manicured the gardens surrounding the palace. The Sunken Garden, located just outside the mansion, is the most famous of them. Human statues in marble and bronze, as well as decorative marble urns, are scattered around the gardens.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\"><strong>The Gates:</strong> The primary and sole magnificent entrance to the palace is located at the end of the Rajmahal Road, among the many gates allowing access to the many parts of the mansion. The king/royal clan have their own gate, which is equally as impressive as the palace itself. This doorway, like the other gates found in Gaekwadi Era structures, has a centre section with a Bengali roof surrounded by two towers and two smaller entrances topped with domes. The structure is made of the same stone as the castle and is embellished with etchings of animals and ornate patterns.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\"><strong>A model railway and a zoo:</strong> The mansion formerly had its own miniature railway and zoo. To transport his children from the school to the main Lakshmi Vilas Palace, the King built a small train line that encircled the mango grove within the palace grounds.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-the-surroundings-of-the-palace\"><strong>The surroundings of the Palace</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\"><strong>The Fatehsinhrao Museum: </strong>The Fatehsinhrao Museum was built as a schoolhouse for the king&#8217;s children. The museum now houses a vast collection of works of art belonging to the royal family. The most notable of these is the magnificent collection of Raja Ravi Varma&#8217;s paintings, which were particularly acquired by the Maharaja of Baroda.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">The museum is well-known among the locals for hosting the yearly Fort Building Competition and the Ganpati Idol Making Competition, both of which are open to both adults and children.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\"><strong>The Cricket Association and the Motibaug Palace:</strong> The Motibaug Palace is really a modest structure that precedes the mansion itself. It was originally built during Maharaja Ganpatrao Gaekwad&#8217;s era to accommodate the State&#8217;s architects and engineers. The Gaekwad Baroda Golf Club&#8217;s main club is now housed there. The Moti Bagh Cricket Ground, the administration of the Baroda Cricket Association, and a very unusual indoor teak coated tennis and badminton court are next to the Motibaug Palace and the Museum.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\"><strong>The Golf Club:</strong> Maharaja Pratapsinhrao built a golf course for his European visitors in the 1930s. The course was rebuilt and offered to the general populace in the 1990s by Pratapsinhrao&#8217;s grandson Samarjitsinh, a renowned Ranji Trophy cricket player. The Gaekwad Baroda Golf Club upgraded the course in 2004 into a magnificent course that presently has over 900 members.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\"><strong>The LVP Banquets:</strong> The LVP Banquets was established a few years ago with a tiny facility comprising of a few large and small halls. The sunken gardens, which are a part of the mansion, are also available for hire by the Banquets for arranging parties and ceremonies.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\"><strong>A massive tree and an ecology: </strong>Over time, the gardens around the palace have acquired their own environment. Around the royal compound, langoors and peacocks may be seen in packs. Aside from that, the complex is home to a massive Banyan tree known as the &#8220;Sayaji Vad,&#8221; which is over a century old and has its own ecology.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-facts-about-lakshmi-vilas-palace\"><strong>Facts about Lakshmi Vilas Palace</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<ol type=\"1\"><li>Did you know that it is known to be the world&#8217;s largest private residence?</li></ol>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>The interiors are reminiscent of a large European country house.</li></ul>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>It had elevators when it was built, which was unusual.</li></ul>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>Prem Rog released in 1982, Dil Hi Toh Hai released in 1993, Sardaar Gabbar Singh released in 2016, and Grand Masti released in 2013, are just a few of the Bollywood films shot in this palace.</li></ul>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-valuation-of-vadodara-s-lakshmi-vilas-palace\"><strong>Valuation of Vadodara&#8217;s Lakshmi Vilas Palace</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">Maharaja Sayajirao Gaekwad III constructed Lakshmi Vilas Palace in 1890 for a staggering \u20b927,00,000 (\u00a31,80,000), which was a considerable sum at that time. The Moti Bagh Cricket Ground, as well as the administration of the well-known Baroda Cricket Association are located near the museum. Navlakhi Vav, a famous stepwell dating from 1405 AD, is also included inside the complex. While it is nearly hard to correctly describe the value of such a massive and intimidating national landmark, estimations suggest that property values in this location might range from \u20b97,000 to \u20b98,000 per Sq. Ft. Taking all into consideration, it is worth noting that the palace compound covers 700 acres or 3,04,92,000 Sq. Ft. Using the current market cost of \u20b98,000 per Sq. Ft as a guide, the ultimate worth would be at least \u20b92,43,93,60,00,000. To put it another way, the Lakshmi Vilas Palace would be valued at a staggering twenty-four thousand three hundred and sixty crores and sixty lakhs. Given the structure&#8217;s cultural significance and history, this figure may potentially reach \u20b925,000 crores.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-ending-remarks\"><strong>Ending Remarks</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">Overall, the palace is the pinnacle of grandeur and a testament of a king who used to be the world&#8217;s eighth richest man. The palace is one of the greatest examples of Indo-Saracenic architecture, which combines Hindu, Mughal, Rajasthani, and Western design. It is adorned with items by some of the world&#8217;s finest artisans. Last but not least, it is a depiction of the splendour of an Indian princely state. Picture the magnificence of India, which at one time had about 800 similar Princely States.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-you-might-also-like\">You Might Also Like</h2>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-yoast-seo-related-links\"><li><a href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog/lets-dig-deep-into-the-grandeur-of-vadodaras-lakshmi-vilas-palace\">Let\u2019s Dig Deep Into The Grandeur of Vadodara\u2019s Lakshmi Vilas Palace</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog/pataudi-palace-taimurs-%e2%82%b9800-cr-royal-inheritance\">Pataudi Palace \u2013 Taimur\u2019s \u20b9800 Cr Royal Inheritance</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog/the-worth-of-mysore-palace-might-surprise-you\">The worth of Mysore Palace might surprise you!</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog/make-your-small-abode-a-happy-place-to-live-in\">Make your  Small Abode a Happy Place to Live in</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog/living-room-decor-ideas-for-cricket-lovers\">Living room decor ideas for cricket lovers</a></li></ul>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-frequently-asked-questions-faq-s\">Freque